      "side": 1,
      "message": "For readers, the distinction of read and readFile is not obvious because their names sound similiar and also they have exactly the exactly same signature.\n\n func read(configFileName, baseDir string, openedFiles map[string]struct{}, sc *block) error\n func readFile(configFileName, baseDir string, openedFiles map[string]struct{}, parentConfig *block) error\nFunction names and argument names are super important documentation for readers. While Go generally recommends shorter names, it doesn\u0027t mean that we can drop meaningful explanations from function/argument names. Please try to name them for readability.\n\nThis comment is closely related to my another comment about paths and globs. You don\u0027t need to use the term \"globs\", let\u0027s say we use a term \"foo\". Then we can change signatures in the following way:\n\n func readFoo(foo, baseDir string, ...) error\n func readPath(path, baseDir string, ...) error",
